ionary warfare]]\n[[Category:Invasions by the Mongol Empire|Europe]]\n[[Category:Invasions of Europe]]\n[[Category:13th-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:Military history of Mongolia|Invasion of Europe]]\n[[Category:13th century in Poland]]\n[[Category:Moldova in the Early Middle Ages]]\n[[Category:13th century in the Mongol Empire|Invasion of Europe]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Teutonic Order]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 1262-65 \u2192 1262\u201365 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mongol_invasion_of_Europe"}
{"title_page": "CKBT-FM", "text_new": "{{short description|Radio station in Kitchener, Ontario}}\n{{Infobox radio station |\n  image     = 91.5 The Beat.png |\n  name      = CKBT-FM|\n  airdate   = January 2004|\n  frequency = 91.5 [[MHz]] ([[FM radio|FM]])|\n  city      = [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Ontario]]|\n  area      = [[Waterloo Regional Municipality|Waterloo Region]]|\n  format    = [[contemporary hit radio|Top 40/CHR]]|\n  owner     = [[Corus Entertainment]]|\n  licensee  = Corus Premium Television Ltd.|\n  sister_stations = [[CJDV-FM]]|\n  erp       = 3,600 [[watt]]s average<br>10,000 [[watt]]s peak |\n  haat      = {{convert|232.5|meters}} |\n  branding  = 91.5 The Beat|\n  slogan    = The #1 Hit Music Station|\n  class     = B|\n  website   = [http://www.915thebeat.com www.915thebeat.com] |\n  callsign_meaning = '''C K'''itchener's '''B'''ea'''T'''|\n}}\n'''CKBT-FM''' is a Canadian radio station broadcasting at 91.5 FM in [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Ontario]]. The station broadcasts a [[contemporary hit radio|Top 40/CHR]] format branded as ''91.5 The Beat'', with studios & offices located in [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], However, its transmitter is south of [[Ayr, Ontario|Ayr]]. The station is owned by [[Corus Entertainment]].\n\nBased on the current format CKBT-FM competes with [[CFCA-FM]].\n\n==History==\n\nThe station was launched by [[CanWest Global]] in January 2004.<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2003/db2003-152.htm Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2003-152]</ref> The original studios were at 235 King Street East, Suite 120, [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]. The station originally aired a [[rhythmic top 40]] format (e.g. [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[reggae]] and [[R&B]]), until switching to its current format in 2005. \n\nIn September 2006, [[Corus Entertainment]], already owner of [[CJDV-FM]] in nearby Cambridge, announced it would buy CKBT and [[Winnipeg]]'s CJZZ-FM (now [[CJGV-FM]]) from CanWest, subject to [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] (CRTC) approval. The transaction was approved by the CRTC on July 6, 2007,<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2007/db2007-215.htm Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2007-215]</ref> and as of July 29, 2007, CKBT was officially made part of Corus Entertainment's radio properties.  \n\nOn August 14, 2009, CKBT moved into a new broadcast facility with brother station [[CJDV-FM]] at 50 Sportsworld Crossing Road, [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]].\n\n[[File:CKBT FM.png|thumb|91.5 The Beat second logo|right|150px]]\n\n== Current Programming ==\n* The Beat Breakfast with Scott Fox & Kat Callaghan - weekday mornings, 5:30am \u2013 9:30am\n* Mid-day's with Melanie - weekdays, 10:00am \u2013 2:00 pm\n* Afternoon Drive with Ell Dee - weekdays, 2:00pm \u2013 6:00pm\n* The Beat Mix @ 6 with DJ Flash - weeknights, 6:00pm \u2013 7:00pm\n* Evenings with Mr.D - weeknights, 7:00pm - 12:00am,\n* Throwback Sunday's with Nicole - Sundays, 12:00pm \u2013 3:00pm\n\n== Former/Notable Hosts & Live-To-Air DJs ==\n*Laura Geddess\n*Carlos Benevides \n*Mike Devine\n*Dave Jutzi\n*Adele Newton (Now with [[CHYM-FM]])\n*Sophie Moroz\n*Mike Farwell\n*Kwame\n*Sandra Klaric\n*AJ (JJ King)\n*Fletch\n*Kathy Wall\n*Christin Parkinson\n*Ru Dawg (Matt Ruiss)\n*Mocha Frap\n*Mike Daddy (Mike Pongracz\n*Silks \"The Prize Guy\"\n*Peter Kash\n*Cash Conners\n*Rob Daniels\n*Stacey Thompson\n\n* DJ Steve Hayward\n* DJ Matt Hodge\n* DJ Rob Bass\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.915thebeat.com 91.5 The Beat] (Official Website)\n* [https://twitter.com/915theBeat Twitter] \n* [https://www.facebook.com/915thebeat Facebook]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/915thebeat Instagram] \n* {{History of Canadian Broadcasting}}\n* {{RecnetCanada|CKBT-FM}}\n\n{{KW Radio}}\n{{Corus Entertainment}}\n{{Contemporary Hit Radio Stations in Ontario}}\n\n{{coord|43|15|39|N|80|26|38|W|type:landmark_region:CA|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ckbt-Fm}}\n[[Category:Radio stations in Kitchener-Waterloo|Kbt]]\n[[Category:Corus Entertainment radio stations|Kbt]]\n[[Category:Contemporary hit radio stations in Canada|Kbt]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in Ontario]]\n\n{{Ontario-radio-station-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Radio station in Kitchener, Ontario}}\n{{Infobox radio station |\n  image     = 91.5 The Beat.png |\n  name      = CKBT-FM|\n  airdate   = January 2004|\n  frequency = 91.5 [[MHz]] ([[FM radio|FM]])|\n  city      = [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Ontario]]|\n  area      = [[Waterloo Regional Municipality|Waterloo Region]]|\n  format    = [[contemporary hit radio|Top 40/CHR]]|\n  owner     = [[Corus Entertainment]]|\n  licensee  = Corus Premium Television Ltd.|\n  sister_stations = [[CJDV-FM]]|\n  erp       = 3,600 [[watt]]s average<br>10,000 [[watt]]s peak |\n  haat      = {{convert|232.5|meters}} |\n  branding  = 91.5 The Beat|\n  slogan    = The #1 Hit Music Station|\n  class     = B|\n  website   = [http://www.915thebeat.com www.915thebeat.com] |\n  callsign_meaning = '''C K'''itchener's '''B'''ea'''T'''|\n}}\n'''CKBT-FM''' is a Canadian radio station broadcasting at 91.5 FM in [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Ontario]]. The station broadcasts a [[contemporary hit radio|Top 40/CHR]] format branded as ''91.5 The Beat'', with studios & offices located in [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], However, its transmitter is south of [[Ayr, Ontario|Ayr]]. The station is owned by [[Corus Entertainment]].\n\nBased on the current format CKBT-FM competes with [[CFCA-FM]].\n\n==History==\n\nThe station was launched by [[CanWest Global]] in January 2004.<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2003/db2003-152.htm Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2003-152]</ref> The original studios were at 235 King Street East, Suite 120, [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]. The station originally aired a [[rhythmic top 40]] format (e.g. [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[reggae]] and [[R&B]]), until switching to its current format in 2005. \n\nIn September 2006, [[Corus Entertainment]], already owner of [[CJDV-FM]] in nearby Cambridge, announced it would buy CKBT and [[Winnipeg]]'s CJZZ-FM (now [[CJGV-FM]]) from CanWest, subject to [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] (CRTC) approval. The transaction was approved by the CRTC on July 6, 2007,<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2007/db2007-215.htm Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2007-215]</ref> and as of July 29, 2007, CKBT was officially made part of Corus Entertainment's radio properties.  \n\nOn August 14, 2009, CKBT moved into a new broadcast facility with brother station [[CJDV-FM]] at 50 Sportsworld Crossing Road, [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]].\n\n[[File:CKBT FM.png|thumb|91.5 The Beat second logo|right|150px]]\n\n== Current Programming ==\n* The Beat Breakfast with Scott Fox & Kat Callaghan - weekday mornings, 5:30am \u2013 9:30am\n* Mid-day's with Melanie - weekdays, 10:00am \u2013 2:00 pm\n* Afternoon Drive with Ell Dee - weekdays, 2:00pm \u2013 6:00pm\n* The Beat Mix @ 6 with DJ Flash - weeknights, 6:00pm \u2013 7:00pm\n* Evenings with Mr.D - weeknights, 7:00pm - 12:00am,\n* Throwback Sunday's with Nicole - Sundays, 12:00pm \u2013 3:00pm\n\n== Former/Notable Hosts & Live-To-Air DJ's ==\n*Laura Geddess\n*Carlos Benevides \n*Mike Devine\n*Dave Jutzi\n*Adele Newton (Now with [[CHYM-FM]])\n*Sophie Moroz\n*Mike Farwell\n*Kwame\n*Sandra Klaric\n*AJ (JJ King)\n*Fletch\n*Kathy Wall\n*Christin Parkinson\n*Ru Dawg (Matt Ruiss)\n*Mocha Frap\n*Mike Daddy (Mike Pongracz\n*Silks \"The Prize Guy\"\n*Peter Kash\n*Cash Conners\n*Rob Daniels\n*Stacey Thompson\n\n* DJ Steve Hayward\n* DJ Matt Hodge\n* DJ Rob Bass\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.915thebeat.com 91.5 The Beat] (Official Website)\n* [https://twitter.com/915theBeat Twitter] \n* [https://www.facebook.com/915thebeat Facebook]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/915thebeat Instagram] \n* {{History of Canadian Broadcasting}}\n* {{RecnetCanada|CKBT-FM}}\n\n{{KW Radio}}\n{{Corus Entertainment}}\n{{Contemporary Hit Radio Stations in Ontario}}\n\n{{coord|43|15|39|N|80|26|38|W|type:landmark_region:CA|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ckbt-Fm}}\n[[Category:Radio stations in Kitchener-Waterloo|Kbt]]\n[[Category:Corus Entertainment radio stations|Kbt]]\n[[Category:Contemporary hit radio stations in Canada|Kbt]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in Ontario]]\n\n{{Ontario-radio-station-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CKBT-FM"}
{"title_page": "Music of Malta", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{prose|date=December 2016}}\n{{expert-subject|Malta|ex2=Regional and national music|date=June 2009}}\n{{unreferenced|date=March 2017}}\n}}\nThe music of [[Malta]] ranges across a spectrum of genres such as traditional [[G\u0127ana (folk music)|folk music]], [[heavy metal music|metal]] and various forms of [[electronica]].\n\n==History==\n\"[[G\u0127ana (folk music)|G\u0127ana]]\" is the traditional folk music of Malta (the 'G\u0127' is a silent consonant).\n\n===Eurovision Song Contest===\nIn 1971 [[Joe Grech]] was the first singer to represent Malta in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. Later, Thea Garrett won the Malta Song for Europe 2010 called ''My Dream''. Lynn Chircop is an infamous Maltese singer who represented Malta at the [[Eurovision 2003]] with a beautiful pop song called \"To Dream Again\". It was sung in Riga with 5 additional backing singers on the stage. Chircop got 4 points at the end of voting process. Morena is another artist who is a winner of Malta Song for Europe 2008 called ''VODKA''. Klinsmann participated in Malta Song for Europe in 2007 [She Gives me Wings] and 2008 [Go finalist song]. Claudia Faniello was the second runner up in Malta song for Europe 2008 who participated with the songs ''Caravaggio'' and ''Sunrise''. Chiara represented Malta in Eurovision a total of 3 times, 1998, 2005, 2009.  [[Gaia Cauchi]] represented and won for Malta in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest in 2013. [[Gianluca Bezzina]] represented Malta in 2013. [[Destiny Chukunyere]] represented and won for Malta in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest in 2015. Chukunyere is going to represent Malta at [[Eurovision 2020]] after winning the Maltese version of X Factor.\n\n==Artists==\n*[[Gabriela N]]\n*[[Antonio Olivari]]\n*[[Arachnid]]\n*[[Beangrowers]]\n*[[Bitterside]]\n*[[BNI (Batteries not Included)]]\n*[[Chasing Pandora]]\n*[[Chiara Siracusa|Chiara]]\n*[[Debbie Scerri]]\n*[[Fabrizio Faniello]]\n*[[Gillian Attard]]\n*[[Hooligan (rapper)|Hooligan]]\n*[[Insurgence]]\n*[[Ira Losco]]\n*[[Julie Zahra]]\n*[[Joe Grech]]\n*[[Knockturn Alley]]\n*[[Lithomancy]]\n*[[Ludwig Galea]]\n*[[Mary Spiteri]]\n*[[The Myth (band)]]\n*[[Olivia Lewis]]\n*[[Ray Buttigieg]]\n*[[Recoil]]\n*[[Renato Micallef]]\n*[[Renzo Spiteri]]\n*[[Roger Scannura]]\n*[[Stalko]]\n*[[Walter Micallef]]\n*[[Wintermoods]]\n\n===Club DJs===\n*[[Adrian V]]\n*[[Alex Grech]]\n*[[Jennings]]\n*[[Miss Roberta]]\n*[[Tenishia]]\n\n===Metal===\n*[[Abysmal Torment]]\n*[[Achiral]]\n*[[Apotheosis]]\n*[[Beheaded (band)|Beheaded]]\n*[[Spin (Maltese band)|Spin]]\n\n==See also==\n*[http://www.vfimf.com/malta-international-music-competition/ Malta International Music Competitions, Valletta/Mdina, Malta]\n* [[List of classical music competitions]]\n* [[Malta in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n* [[Malta in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest]]\n* [[Malta Music Awards]]\n* [[Malta Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n* [[Sine Macula Choir]]\n\n===Instruments===\n* [[\u017baqq]]\n* [[Friction drum]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vfimf.com Malta International Music Master Classes, VFIMF Festival, Malta International Music Competition]\n*[http://central-academy.com/violin-making-competition/ Malta International Violin/Viola/Bow Making Competition and Instrumental Master Classes]\n*[http://central-academy.com/ Central Academy of Arts]\n*[http://www.maltamusiconline.com Malta Music Online - Website sharing Maltese Music Bands' information]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090716193329/http://www.music.com.mt/ Music of Malta]\n*[http://www.maltavoyager.com/downloads_maltesemusic.html MaltaVoyager]\n*[http://www.basement.com.mt/ Dance music and clubbing in Malta]\n*[http://www.alternativemalta.com - Maltese alternative scene]\n*[http://www.technoelectro.com/ Maltese Techno and Electro Music scene]\n*[http://vfimf.com Malta International Music Master Classes and more cultural projects and courses]\n*[http://www.maltanetworkresources.com/ Maltese Music Internet Radio at Malta Network Resources]\n\n{{Malta topics}}\n{{Music of Europe}}\n\n[[Category:Maltese music]]\n\n{{Malta-stub}}\n{{music-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{prose|date=December 2016}}\n{{expert-subject|Malta|ex2=Regional and national music|date=June 2009}}\n{{unreferenced|date=March 2017}}\n}}\nThe music of [[Malta]] ranges across a spectrum of genres such as traditional [[G\u0127ana (folk music)|folk music]], [[heavy metal music|metal]] and various forms of [[electronica]].\n\n==History==\n\"[[G\u0127ana (folk music)|G\u0127ana]]\" is the traditional folk music of Malta (the 'G\u0127' is a silent consonant).\n\n===Eurovision Song Contest===\nIn 1971 [[Joe Grech]] was the first singer to represent Malta in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. Later, Thea Garrett won the Malta Song for Europe 2010 called ''My Dream''. Lynn Chircop is an infamous Maltese singer who represented Malta at the [[Eurovision 2003]] with a beautiful pop song called \"To Dream Again\". It was sung in Riga with 5 additional backing singers on the stage. Chircop got 4 points at the end of voting process. Morena is another artist who is a winner of Malta Song for Europe 2008 called ''VODKA''. Klinsmann participated in Malta Song for Europe in 2007 [She Gives me Wings] and 2008 [Go finalist song]. Claudia Faniello was the second runner up in Malta song for Europe 2008 who participated with the songs ''Caravaggio'' and ''Sunrise''. Chiara represented Malta in Eurovision a total of 3 times, 1998, 2005, 2009.  [[Gaia Cauchi]] represented and won for Malta in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest in 2013. [[Gianluca Bezzina]] represented Malta in 2013. [[Destiny Chukunyere]] represented and won for Malta in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest in 2015. Chukunyere is going to represent Malta at [[Eurovision 2020]] after winning the Maltese version of X Factor.\n\n==Artists==\n*[[Gabriela N]]\n*[[Antonio Olivari]]\n*[[Arachnid]]\n*[[Beangrowers]]\n